<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,249,850]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,429,454]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Remarks.</emphasis>
The hydroid briefly described as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fraser" authorityYear="1914" box="[714,960,429,454]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Ophiodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="carchesium">
<emphasis box="[714,960,429,454]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Ophiodes carchesium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation box="[1010,1179,429,454]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref74900" refString="Fraser, C. M. (1914 b) Notes on some Αlaskan hydroids. Transactions of the Royal Society of Canada, Series 3, Section 4, 8, 217 - 222. [December 1914: date on issue number of the journal]" type="journal article">Fraser (1914b)</bibRefCitation>
was found in a small collection from halibut grounds in the Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[713,794,465,490]" country="United States of America" name="Alaska" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Alaska</collectingRegion>
, provided by Dr. Arthur Willey of McGill University, Montreal, 
<collectingCountry box="[270,358,501,526]" name="Canada" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Canada</collectingCountry>
. The specimen, sterile and simple in morphology, was growing as an epizoite on a bryozoan colony. Material in the Fraser Hydroid Collection at the 
<collectionCode box="[818,899,537,561]" country="Canada" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/gayt-20cg" name="Royal British Columbia Museum" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">RBCM</collectionCode>
(
<collectionCode box="[917,997,537,561]" country="Canada" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/aa64-5nmw" name="British Columbia Provincial Museum" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">BCPM</collectionCode>
976-00508-001), comprising a single colony consistent with both the descriptive account and illustration in 
<bibRefCitation box="[944,1105,573,598]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref74900" refString="Fraser, C. M. (1914 b) Notes on some Αlaskan hydroids. Transactions of the Royal Society of Canada, Series 3, Section 4, 8, 217 - 222. [December 1914: date on issue number of the journal]" type="journal article">Fraser (1914b</bibRefCitation>
: figs. 1a, b), is considered by us to be the 
<typeStatus box="[287,385,609,634]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">holotype</typeStatus>
by monotypy (
<collectionCode box="[556,623,610,634]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">ICZN</collectionCode>
Art. 73.1.2). The specimen and its bryozoan substrate have now slipped beyond the coverslip of the slide, but are still embedded in 
<collectingCountry box="[814,898,645,670]" name="Canada" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Canada</collectingCountry>
balsam.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,249,850]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Known only from the original account, the species is listed as 
<taxonomicName authority="in Rees &amp; Vervoort (1987)" authorityName="in Rees &amp; Vervoort" authorityYear="1987" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Hydrodendron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="carchesium">
<emphasis box="[908,1207,681,706]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Hydrodendron carchesium</emphasis>
in 
<bibRefCitation pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref81854" refString="Rees, W. J. &amp; Vervoort, W. (1987) Hydroids from the John Murray Expedition to the Indian Ocean, with revisory notes on Hydrodendron, Abietinella, Cryptolaria and Zygophylax (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa). Zoologische Verhandelingen, 237, 1 - 209." type="journal article">Rees &amp; Vervoort (1987)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation box="[240,463,717,742]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref72164" refString="Cairns, S. D., Calder, D. R., Brinckmann-Voss, Α., Castro, C. B., Fautin, D. G., Pugh, P. R., Mills, C. E., Jaap, W. C., Αrai, M. N., Haddock, S. H. D. &amp; Opresko, D. M. (2002) Common and scientific names of aquatic invertebrates from the United States and Canada: Cnidaria and Ctenophora. Second Edition. American Fisheries Society Special Publication, 28, 1 - 115." type="journal article">
Cairns 
<emphasis box="[321,370,717,742]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">et al</emphasis>
. (2002)
</bibRefCitation>
, and WoRMS. The specific name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="in Rees &amp; Vervoort" authorityYear="1987" box="[850,978,717,742]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Hydrodendron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="carchesium">
<emphasis box="[850,978,717,742]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">carchesium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a noun in apposition (Latin: a kind of drinking cup) and need not agree in gender with any generic name with which it is combined (
<collectionCode box="[1206,1273,754,778]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">ICZN</collectionCode>
Art. 31.2.1).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,249,850]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
The family 
<taxonomicName authority="Stechow, 1921 a" authorityName="Stechow" authorityYear="1921" box="[339,723,789,814]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Phylactothecidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="family">
Phylactothecidae 
<bibRefCitation box="[542,723,789,814]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref82892" refString="Stechow, E. (1921 a) Neue Genera und Species von Hydrozoen und anderen Evertebraten. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte, Αbteilung Α., Heft 3, 87, 248 - 265." type="journal article">Stechow, 1921a</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is recognized here as valid following 
<bibRefCitation box="[1182,1432,789,814]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref73028" refString="Choong, H. H. C., Calder, D. R., Chapman, J. W., Miller, J. Α., Geller, J. B. &amp; Carlton, J. T. (2018) Hydroids (Cnidaria: Hydrozoa: Leptothecata and Limnomedusae) on 2011 Japanese tsunami marine debris landing in North Αmerica and Hawai'i, with revisory notes on Hydrodendron Hincks, 1874 and a diagnosis of Plumaleciidae, new family. Aquatic Invasions, 13, 43 - 70. https: // doi. org / 10.3391 / ai. 2018.13.1.05" type="journal article">
Choong 
<emphasis box="[1282,1336,789,814]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">et al</emphasis>
. (2018)
</bibRefCitation>
. Included within it are 
<taxonomicName authorityName="in Rees &amp; Vervoort" authorityYear="1987" box="[398,560,825,850]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Hydrodendron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="carchesium">
<emphasis box="[398,560,825,850]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">H. carchesium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Hincks, 1874" authorityName="Hincks" authorityYear="1874" box="[911,1234,825,850]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Hydrodendron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[911,1074,825,850]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Hydrodendron</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[1081,1234,825,850]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref78727" refString="Hincks, T. (1874) Notes on Norwegian Hydroida from deep water. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 4, 13, 125 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222937408680824" type="journal article">Hincks, 1874</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
